# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aport-apple
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aport-apple/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:aport-apple/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:aport-apple/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:aport-apple/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:aport-apple/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:aport-apple/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:aport-apple/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:aport-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:aport-apple/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:aport-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:aport-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:aport-apple/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:aport-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:aport-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:aport-apple/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:aport-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:aport-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:aport-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:aport-apple/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:aport-apple/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:aport-apple/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:aport-apple/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:aport-apple/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:aport-apple/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:aport-apple/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:aport-apple/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:aport-apple/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:aport-apple/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is in the foothills of the Trans-Ili Alatau mountains in southern Kazakhstan, near the border with Kyrgyzstan, at an elevation of 700–900 metres (2,300–3,000 feet), with the Big Almaty and Small Almaty rivers running through it.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty is the second-largest city in Central Asia and the fourth-largest in the Commonwealth of Independent States.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty was the capital of Kazakhstan from 1929 to 1991 (during the Soviet era) and after independence from 1991 until the capital was moved to Akmola (now Astana) in 1997.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is classified as a city of republican significance.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty has hosted international events, including the Alma-Ata Primary Healthcare Conference in 1978, the 2011 Asian Winter Games, and the 2017 Winter Universiade.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The city was also a contender to host the 2022 Winter Olympics, but ultimately lost the bid to Beijing.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It has been a UNESCO Creative City of Music since 2017, and classified as a Gamma + level global city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Landmarks and attractions in Almaty include the Central State Museum of Kazakhstan; Ascension Cathedral; Green Bazaar; Arbat, a pedestrian area; and Kök Töbe, a hilltop recreation area with views of the city and the surrounding mountains.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The city is also home to educational institutions such as Al-Farabi Kazakh National University, the Kazakh-British Technical University, the International Information Technology University, and Narxoz University.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] From 1929 to 1936, the city, then known as Alma-Ata, was the capital of the Kazakh ASSR.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] From 1936 to 1991, Alma-Ata was the capital of the Kazakh SSR.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] After Kazakhstan became independent in 1991, the city was renamed Almaty in 1993 and continued as the capital until 1997, when the capital was moved to Akmola (renamed Astana in 1998, Nur-Sultan in 2019, and again Astana in 2022).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Since then Almaty has been referred to as the "southern capital" of Kazakhstan, whose largest and most ethnically diverse city it remains.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The name *Almaty* has its roots in the medieval settlement *Almatau*, that existed near the present-day city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] A disputed theory holds that the name is derived from the Kazakh word for 'apple' (алма), and is often translated as "full of apples".
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] "Its former name, Alma-Ata, translates to 'father of the apples'".
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Its current name could be a pluralization of a Turkic word for "father".
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is mentioned in the 16th-century *Bāburnāma* under the spelling *Almatu* (Chagatay: الماتو).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Its past name was Almatau, meaning 'Apple Mountain'.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] There is genetic diversity among the wild apples in the Almaty region; the region west of the Tian Shan mountains is thought to be the apple's ancestral home.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Nikolay Vavilov suggested the *Malus sieversii* is a candidate for the ancestor of the modern domestic apple.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] During 1000–900 BC in the Bronze Age, the first farmers and cattle-breeders established settlements in the territory of Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The most famous archaeological finds have been "The Golden Man", also known as "The Golden Warrior", from the Issyk Kurgan; the Zhalauly treasure, the Kargaly diadem, and the Zhetysu arts bronzes (boilers and altars).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] During the period of Saka and Wusun governance, Almaty became an early education center.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The region comprising modern Almaty and its surroundings was ruled by the Qara Khitai during the 12th century until they were invaded by the Mongol empire in 1218.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It remained under the Mongols until the disintegration of the empire at the end of the century after which the region continued to be a part of the subsequent Chagatai Khanate, or later the breakaway Moghulistan.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] This region was an important trade route between the West and East, with cities like Taraz to the west and Almaliq to the east as major stopping points.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The importance declined during the 15th century though, due to Temür’s attacks and him shifting the trade routes southwards, whereafter Tarim basin became the centre for Moghulistan.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Wars with Timur, Bukhara Khanate and Kazakh Khanate decreased Moghul’s rule in Transoxonia over the 15th century and by early 16th century, the Almaty region came under the Kazakh rule.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Dzungar invaded, dominating the Kazakh people for a period.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Kazakhs fought to protect their land and preserve independence.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1730 the Kazakh defeated the Dzungar in the Anyrakay mountains, 70 kilometres (45 miles) northwest of Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Senior Kazakh Horde (Uly Zhuz) held jurisdiction over the region.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] During the eighteenth century, the city and region were near the border of the Khanate of Kokand.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It was then absorbed as part of the Russian Empire in the 1850s.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] To establish its control of the region, Russia built **Fort Zailiyskoe** (Russian: Заилийское) between the Bolshaya and Malenkaya Almatinka rivers.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Construction began on 4 February 1854 and was largely completed by autumn.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The fort was a pentagonal wooden palisade with one side built along the Malaya Almatinka.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Before the end of the year, it was renamed **Fort Vernoe** (Верное, "Loyal"), sometimes rendered as Vyernoe at the time.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The palisade was eventually replaced with a brick wall with embrasures.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The fort's main facilities were erected around the large central square for training and parading.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1867, the settlement around the fort was so large it was reorganized as the town of **Almatinsk** (Алматинск).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Before the end of the year, this was renamed **Verny** (Верный, *Vernyj*).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 28 May 1887, at 4 a.m., an earthquake narrowly destroyed Verny in 11–12 minutes.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] By 1906, the population of the city had grown to 27,000, two-thirds of whom were Russians and Ukrainians.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 3 January 1911, the city was almost completely destroyed with over 770 brick buildings collapsing as a result of the 1911 Kebin earthquake.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1918 following the Russian Revolution and the establishment of the Bolshevik government, Soviet power was established in Verny.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The city and the region became part of the Turkestan Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic (RSFSR).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 5 February 1921, Verny was renamed Alma-Ata, one of the city's ancient names, by a joint consultation of regional government representatives, professional trade associations, and local faith-based groups.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1926, the Council of Labor and Defence approved the construction of the Turkestan–Siberia Railway that was a crucial element of the future growth of Kazakhstan, especially in the east and southeast of the region.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Turkestan–Siberia Railway construction had a decisive economic impact that influenced the destiny of Alma-Ata as the capital of the Kazakh ASSR.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1930, the construction of the highway and railway to Alma-Ata was completed.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 29 April 1927, the government decided to transfer the capital of the Kazakh Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic from Kyzyl-Orda to Alma-Ata, within the RFSFR.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] This attracted more trade and people working with the government, stimulating intensive development in the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 31 January 1928, Leon Trotsky, leader of the 1917 October Revolution, accompanied by his wife Natalia Sedova and his son Lev Sedov, was exiled to Alma-Ata by Joseph Stalin, then head of the All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks) in Moscow.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Trotsky was expelled from Alma-Ata to Turkey in February 1929 and went into exile in Mexico City.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Alma-Ata airport was opened in 1930, opening up a connection from Alma-Ata to Moscow, the center of the Soviet government.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Alma-Ata became the main entry by air to Kazakhstan, a status which it retains today.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Transformation of this small town into the capital of the Kazakh SSR was accelerated by the large-scale construction of new administrative and government facilities and housing.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Great Purge of 1936–38 extended to Kazakhstan, where numerous people were killed.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Soviet government dominated the population.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] During the 1930s Kazakh nomads suffered starvation after disruption of their traditional living patterns.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1936 the Architecture and Planning Bureau developed a plan to enhance Alma-Ata as the new cultural capital of the Kazakh SSR.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The plan was based on the existing rectangular system of districts.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] They are to be strengthened and reconstructed.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] During World War II the government affected the city's population and structures.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] To better organize the home front and concentrate industrial and material resources, the government evacuated 26,000 people and numerous industries from the European theatre of war.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Alma-Ata hosted over 30 industrial facilities removed from the European section of the USSR, eight evacuated hospitals, 15 institutes, universities and technical schools; and around 20 cultural institutions.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Motion picture production companies from Leningrad, Kyiv, and Moscow were also moved to Alma-Ata at this time.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] This brought in so many ethnic Russians that the Kazakhs became a minority in the region.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In connection with the formation of the Polish Anders' Army, a Polish diplomatic post was located in the city from October 1941 to July 1942.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] During the years 1941–1945, industrial development increased during the postwar years.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] By 1967 the city had 145 enterprises, with the bulk of these being light and food industries.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The main industries in Alma-Ata were: food processing (36% of gross industrial output), light industry (31%), and heavy industry (33%).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] From 1966 to 1971, 1,400,000 square metres of public and cooperative housing were built.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Annually, around 300,000 square metres of dwellings were under construction.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Most of the buildings constructed during this time were earthquake-proof multi-story buildings.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Soviet government tried to diversify architectural forms to create a more varied cityscape.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] During this period, many schools, hospitals, cultural, and entertainment facilities were constructed, including Lenin's Palace, the Kazakhstan Hotel, and the Medeo Sports Complex.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The supersonic transport Tupolev Tu-144 went into service on 26 December 1975, carrying mail and freight between Moscow and Alma-Ata in preparation for passenger services; these began in November 1977.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Aeroflot flight on 1 June 1978 was the 55th and last scheduled passenger flight of the Tu-144.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Alma-Ata was the host city for a 1978 international conference on Primary Health Care.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Alma Ata Declaration was adopted, marking a paradigm shift in global public health.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 16 December 1986, the Jeltoqsan riot took place in the Brezhnev Square (now Republic Square) in response to General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev's dismissal of Dinmukhamed Kunayev.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 7 September 1988, the subway Almaty Metro project began construction, and the subway was opened on 1 December 2011 after 23 years.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Kazakhstan declared its independence from the Soviet Union on 16 December 1991 (Kazakhstan Independence Day).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 28 January 1993, the government renamed the city from the Russian *Alma-Ata* to the Kazakh name *Almaty*.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1997 the President of the Republic of Kazakhstan Nursultan Nazarbayev approved the decree to transfer the capital from Almaty to Astana in the north of the country.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 1 July 1998 a law was passed to establish the special status of Almaty as a scientific, cultural, historical, financial, and industrial centre.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The new general plan of Almaty for 2030 was released in 1998.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is intended to create ecologically safe and socially comfortable living conditions in the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The main objective is to promote Almaty's image as a garden-city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It proposes continued multi-storied and single-housing development, reorganization of industrial districts or territories, improving transport infrastructure, and expanding the Almaty Metro.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The first line of the Almaty metro was launched on 1 December 2011, two weeks ahead of schedule.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The extension of the line to Qalqaman was opened in 2015.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Nevertheless, Almaty has developed a major problem with air pollution.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Already in 1995, particulate emissions, then from the city's thermal power station, exceeded Kazakh and EU standards by over 20 times.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 2008, Almaty was ranked the 9th most polluted city in the world.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] An independent local air quality monitoring system with a mobile app was launched in 2017.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The area of the city has been expanded during recent years with the annexation of the suburban settlements of Kalkaman, Kok Tobe, Gorniy Gigant District (Mountain Giant).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Numerous apartment blocks and office skyscrapers have transformed the face of the town, which has been built into the mountains.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Squatter settlements such as Shanyrak have resisted eviction in the face of these development plans.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty was the site of a notorious terrorist attack in July 2016, when Jihadist Ruslan Kulikbayev killed eight police officers and two civilians in a shootout and car chase.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Kulikbayev was wounded during the shootout and later sentenced to death for the attack.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In March 2020, the first cases of COVID-19 were reported in the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Soon, Almaty was transformed, as the pandemic led the city into a changed behavior.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The government imposed lockdowns of most institutions.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In January 2022, Almaty was plunged into unrest as part of a national political crisis.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty is located in south-eastern Kazakhstan, almost 1000 km from the capital Astana.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Kyrgyzstan's capital Bishkek is 190 km to the west, while Ürümqi in China is almost 1000 km east.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The region is also home to the Mynjylky mountain plateau, an elevated plain located at the source of the Malaya Almaatinka river at an altitude of 3000 meters above sea level.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty has a humid continental climate (Köppen climate classification: *Dfa*) with hot summers and cold winters.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is characterized by the influence of mountain–valley circulation.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] This is evident in the northern part of the city, located directly in the transition zone of the mountain slopes to the plains.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Annual average air temperature is equal to 10 °C (50 °F), the coldest month is January, −4.7 °C (24 °F) (on average), the warmest month (July) 23.8 °C (75 °F) (on average).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In average years frost starts on about 14 October and ends on about 18 April, with sustained extreme cold from about 19 December to about 23 February, a period of about 67 days.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Weather with temperature above 30 °C (86 °F) is average for about 36 days a year.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In the center of Almaty, like any large city, there is a heat island.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Therefore, frost in the city center starts about 7 days later and finishes 3 days earlier than in the northern suburbs.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Annual precipitation is about 650 to 700 mm (25.6 to 27.6 in).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] April and May are the wettest months, during which about a third of the city's annual precipitation is received.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is not uncommon to see snow hitting Almaty as late as the end of May, as in the last quarter century, such snowfalls were recorded on 13 May 1985, 1 May 1989, 5 May 1993 and 18 May 1998.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty sometimes experiences winter rain, even with heavy preceding snowfall and low temperatures.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The most memorable winter rain took place on 16 December 1996 during a military parade to celebrate the 5th anniversary of the Independence of the Republic.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty Weather Station's GM records south-easterly wind (30%), its resistance increases during the summer (37%) and falls in winter (19%).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Wind speeds exceed 15 m/s on about 15 days a year, on average.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Industrially developed and populated areas in the south and southeast of Kazakhstan are situated in the zones where the maximum magnitudes of expected earthquakes are from 6.0 to 8.3 (the intensity of I0=8–10).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The south seismic active zone of Kazakhstan is a part of the North Tian-Shan ridge system.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The main city of Almaty is located near the Zailiski Alatau mountain base.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In recorded history prior to the late 19th century, three catastrophic earthquakes are known to have taken place there.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Within the past 125 years, three more strong destructive earthquakes occurred here, with centres not more than 20–130 kilometres (10–80 mi) from the current city location.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Their magnitudes were 9 and 11 on the MSK scale – 64, and their centres were located within 100 kilometres (60 mi).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In each of these earthquakes, the city suffered wide destruction.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Territory of the Kyrgyz State adjoins North Tian-Shan.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty was, in 2020, considered to be "Kazakhstan's cultural capital", as contemporary Almaty has a more European character due to more cafes and restaurants with outdoor seating and public green space.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty is the historical capital of intellectualism in Kazakhstan as a product of Almaty's location along the Silk Road, and because many Russian intellectuals were exiled to the region.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Abai Kazakh State Opera and Ballet Theatre has placed the city's theater scene since 1934 and was founded around a community of local performance artists.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Kasteyev State Museum of Arts was founded in 1935, is the largest museum in Kazakhstan, and has the largest collection of artworks by Kazakh classic and contemporary artists.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The wild apple *Malus sieversii* is generally accepted as having first emerged in the Almaty area and figure in Almaty's culture.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Theatrical art began to develop in the city of Verny a few years after the construction of the Russian fort.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On 21 November 1872, the Society of Dramatic Art Lovers staged the first production in the city: A.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Ostrovsky's play, "Stay in Your Own Sled".
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Later, plays were performed at public, military, and commercial gatherings.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] An abridgement of Glinka's opera "A Life for the Tsar" was the first opera staged in the city, by the Kolpakovsky three-year city school on 23 February 1913 at the Commercial Assembly, to commemorate the tercentenary of the Romanov dynasty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The flowering of theatrical art in the city began during the Soviet period of Alma-Ata, resulting from the transfer of the capital of the Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic from Kyzylorda to Alma-Ata.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Thus, the Kazakh Drama Theater, the first Kazakh professional theater, moved to the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In the 1930s, the Opera and Ballet Theater (1934) and the Puppet Theater (1935) were established in the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] After Kazakhstan regained independence in 1991, a large number of new independent theaters appeared in the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Often these are modern youth concert venues created by enthusiasts.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] They face funding problems, as maintaining a permanent theater company is costly.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] A contribution to the study of the history of culture, ethnography of southern Kazakhs in the late 19th–20th centuries was made by Turkestan scientists and local historians, united around the scientific societies and cultural and educational institutions of Tashkent.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1874, from the private collections of travelers who visited Semirechye with a scientific and regional purpose and with the help of the local intelligentsia, a museum was first created in the city of Verny, which was later transformed into a village museum of the Semirechye Cossack Host.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] This date is the day of the foundation of the first museum in Semirechye.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Kasteev Museum of Arts was laid by the Kazakh State Art Gallery named after T.G.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Its main tasks were to collect the best works of Kazakh artists and organize their creative business trips.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1936, museums in Moscow and Leningrad (now St.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Petersburg) donated a significant number of paintings, graphics, sculpture and applied art to the gallery.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] By the end of the 1950s, the gallery's funds numbered over 5,000 exhibits, including paintings, reproductions of works by pre-revolutionary and Soviet artists, Western European and Eastern masters of art.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In the 1970s and 1980s, new buildings were built for existing museums, and new thematic museums were opened: books, musical instruments, archeology, and others.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] A significant contribution to the development of the museum business was the opening of the Museum of the History of Almaty, which created an association of museums in the city of Almaty and the state institution "Gylym Ordasy", which united 4 museums, which allows to systematize scientific work.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The first film screening in the city of Verny took place in 1900, when the physicist K.O.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] On it, hand-painted glass transparencies were demonstrated with the help of an overhead projector.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The film show took place on 25 January in the Pushkin Garden.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In January 1911, the building of the first private cinema "Twentieth Century" was opened at the intersection of Pushkin and Gogol streets, which belonged to the entrepreneur A.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] For the demonstration of films, the cinema was equipped with the first power plant in the history of the city, produced by the British company "Petter", with 14 horsepower.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The cinema building burned down in February 1918.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Starting in the 1930s, summer cinemas began to appear in the parks of the city, which were later transformed into full-fledged cinemas.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Thus, the Rodina Cinema was first opened in the Central Park in 1937.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1957, it was rebuilt from a seasonal venue into a wide-screen cinema with an auditorium for 712 seats.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In another park of the city, the Park of the Federation of Soviet Republics, the Progress Cinema was opened, later renamed Alma-Ata.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] By the early 1990s, there were 21 cinemas in the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] All cinemas were divided into first, second and third screens.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The cinemas of the first screen, in which the premieres of new films took place, were "Alatau", "Tselinny" and "Arman".
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Film films arrived at the cinemas of the third screen in a deplorable state, with glues and cuts.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] That is, the quality of showing the film depended on the screening of the cinema.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Cinemas in the city were single-screen, two halls were owned by the cinema centers "Kazakhstan", "Arman" and "Tselinny".
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In the 2000s, cinemas began to open in shopping and entertainment centers, and as a result, existing stationary cinemas began to lose popularity and close.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty generates approximately 20% of Kazakhstan's GDP (or $36 billion in 2010).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The city accounts for about 20% of government revenues and 60% of bank credits.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty is also a financial center, as is considered to be a Beta-Global City as of the 2012 GaWC study.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] One of the industries in Almaty is finance, and its financial exports make it a large contributor to Kazakhstan's balance of payments.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty is home to Halyk Bank, which is the largest bank in Central Asia, Kaspi Bank, and other major banks.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Kazakhstan Stock Exchange is based in Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty is also developing as a regional financial and business centre (RFCA).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Under construction is the 'Almaty Financial District and Esentai Park'.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Gottesdiener, who designed both 7 World Trade Center in New York City and Tokyo Midtown.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Its goal is to become the largest business centre in Central Asia.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Esentai Tower, a 37-floor building in the park, is the tallest mixed-use building in Kazakhstan, housing offices of companies such as Ernst & Young, HSBC and Credit Suisse.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The first Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Kazakhstan opened in 2013 in Esentai Tower.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Media companies are concentrated in Almaty, as the media distribution industry has been growing rapidly since 2006.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Major broadcasting channels KTK and NTK are based in Almaty, as are several national newspapers.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Western Europe – Western China Highway passes through Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] A new airport in Almaty expects to handle about 45 million tonnes of cargo each year.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 2010, Air Astana was headquartered in Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Before their dissolution, Air Kazakhstan and Kazakhstan Airlines were also headquartered in Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 1854, the Tsarist government built a military fortification on the left bank of the Almaty River.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The construction was supervised by Major Peremyshelsky and engineer-lieutenant Aleksandrovsky.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] By the autumn of the same year, construction work was completed.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] With their arrival, the area of Almaty began to develop rapidly, and buildings were constructed during this time including the Little Stanitsa and the Tatar Slobodka.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] A major earthquake in 1887 destroyed 1798 brick houses and killed 322 people.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] After the earthquake, numerous buildings were constructed including the House of the Regiment of Military Assembly (1908), Ascension Cathedral, the House of Public Assembly, and others.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] At the time, Zenkov was in charge of the construction projects of the Semirechye regional government.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] From 1966 to 1972, most of the buildings constructed during the era were earthquake-proof multi-story housing blocks.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] During this period, many schools, hospitals, cultural, and entertainment facilities were constructed in post-modernist style, including Lenin's Palace (now Palace of the Republic, 1970), Hotel Kazakhstan (1977) and the Medeu (1971).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] According to the city's Department of Natural Resources and Resource Use Management, as of 2007 the city had 125 fountains.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Among them is the "Oriental Calendar" Fountain, whose 12 sculptural figures represent the 12 animals of the Kazakh 12-year animal cycle (similar to its Chinese counterpart).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] There are now more than 120 fountains in Almaty, 61 of which are communally owned.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Fountains, together with an extensive irrigation ditch network, play a big role in Alma-Ata – together they create a single complex of reservoirs and watercourses of the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Every year at the end of spring, the city celebrates the "Day of Fountains" holiday where for the first time after winter, all the city's fountains are turned on.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 2006, a new fountain was opened on Lake Sayran.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Previously, the highest fountain in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) gushed from this lake – a stream of water 10 cm in diameter reached a height of 50 meters.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The fountain has been closed since 2008.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Medeu is an outdoor speed skating and bandy rink.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is located in a mountain valley (Medeu Valley, or the valley of Malaya Alma-Atinka River) on the south-eastern outskirts of Almaty, Kazakhstan.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Medeu sits 1,691 metres above sea level, making it one of the highest skating rinks in the world.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It has 10,500 square meters of ice and utilizes a sophisticated freezing and watering system to ensure the quality of the ice.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Medeu was re-built in 1972 in the gorge of the same name, 15 km from the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] "Medeo" was called "the factory of records", since 126 world records were set on the ice of a high-mountain skating rink in 33 years.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The ice rink, located at an altitude of 1700 m in thin air and high quality ice, is provided by pure mountain water without admixture of salts.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In addition, Above the sports complex there is a mudflow protection dam and the Shymbulak.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In the 1990s, the Medeu was the venue for the Voice of Asia international music festival (Asia Dauysy).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Şymbūlaq is a ski resort near Almaty, located in the upper part of the Medeu Valley in the Zailiisky Alatau mountain range, at the elevation of 2,200 metres (7,200 ft) above sea level.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The resort area is about 25 kilometres (16 mi) south of Almaty city by the Medeu road.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is popular for its mild climate, a large quantity of sunny days and a great amount of snow through the winter (from November until May).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The resort offers both day and night skiing.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The ski resort also hold a Guinness world record for the worlds highest ski slope available for night skiing.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Big Almaty Lake is a natural lake located in Trans-Ili Alatau mountains on 2511 above the sea level near Almaty (15 km South from Almaty).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Like a majority of lakes in Trans-Ili Alatau, this lake formed as the result of an earthquake.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The lake is a major source of drinking water for the region.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] People can access the lake by car (approximately 1 hour drive from the city center), bike, or hiking (approximately a half-day trip).
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The First President's Park is an urban park located in Almaty at the intersection of Navoi Street and Al-Farabi Avenue in the Bostandyq District.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The park is broken into three main areas–the avenue, boulevard, and dendrological areas.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Greenery was planted according to dendrological plan.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In honor of the participation of the city of Almaty in the Olympic torch relay of the Beijing Olympic Games, approximately one hundred spruces and birches were planted.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 2011, a hundred Tien-Shan spruces were also planted.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Plans include a set of water projects over an area of 9.5 hectares.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] An aerial tramway line connects Almaty with a popular recreation area at the top of Kök Töbe (Kazakh: Көк-төбе, which means 'Blue Hill'), a mountain just to the southeast.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The city television tower, Almaty Tower, is located on the hill.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It was built in between 1978 and 1983, and is 371.5 m tall.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The TV tower, located at an altitude of 1000 m above sea level, is the tallest structure in Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Its height is almost 372 m, and it sits at an elevation of 1130 m.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The base of the tower is a reinforced concrete foundation in the form of a three-storey sectional basement.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The barrel of the tower is a metal stepped hexahedron with a diameter of 18 m at the base, 13 and 9 m at the locations of maintenance services at heights of 146 and 252 m.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The structure was built taking into account the seismic mountainous terrain and can withstand an earthquake of up to 10 points.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The television tower is a complex of an operating radio and television transmitting station with a special mode of operation, therefore it is inaccessible for sightseeing tours of the city from a height.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The tower, illuminated at night by powerful searchlights, is visible from almost anywhere in the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Park of 28 Panfilov Guardsmen is a major park in Almaty, Kazakhstan.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The park is located in east-central Almaty in the area surrounding Zenkov Cathedral.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] It is dedicated to and named after the Panfilov Heroes, 28 soldiers of an Almaty infantry unit who died fighting Nazi German invaders outside of Moscow in World War II.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The group takes its name from Ivan Panfilov, the General commanding the 316th division which, in spite of heavy casualties, believed at that time managed to delay the Germans' advance on the capital, buying time for the defenders of the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] An eternal flame commemorating the fallen of the Russian Civil War and the Great Patriotic War burns in front of the giant black monument of soldiers from all 15 Soviet republics.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The closest airport to Almaty is Almaty International Airport located 15 kilometres (9+1⁄2 mi) northeast of the city centre.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Sayran Bus Terminal provides intercity bus connections within Kazakhstan, as well as international connections to Kyrgyzstan and China and regional bus connections west of the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Sayakhat Bus Terminal provides regional bus connections to places north and east of the city.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Kazakhstan Temir Joly has two stations: Almaty-1 (located 20 minutes drive from the city center, and reserved mostly for cargo) and Almaty-2 located within the city and reserved for passengers.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] In 2011 the Almaty Metro opened, and a light rail line was built in 2011.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] A bicycle-sharing system, Almaty-bike, has been in operation since September 2016.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] People can buy a monthly card and ride freely.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The historic bandy team Dinamo won the Soviet Championships in 1977 and 1990 and the European Cup in 1978.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Bandy was introduced for the first time at the 2011 Winter Asian Games.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Medeu was the main arena at the 2012 Bandy World Championship.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The second arena built for the championships is an alternative field at Almaty Central Stadium.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The city is now a candidate to host also the 2020 Bandy World Championship.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Federation of International Bandy has opened an office for Asia, which is located in Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty was the host of the 2017 Winter Universiade with bandy on the programme.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The 2011 Asian Winter Games were held jointly in Almaty and Astana.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The ice hockey and ski jumping competitions were held in the city at the Baluan Sholak Sports Palace and Sunkar International Ski Jumping Complex respectively.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The biathlon, cross-country skiing, and ski orienteering competitions were held at the nearby Soldatskoe Valley Cross Country Skiing and Biathlon Stadium; the Alpine skiing and bandy competitions were held in nearby Shymbulak and Medeo respectively.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The Yenbek Almaty ice hockey team played from 1965 to 1985 and from 1999 to 2009.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] HC Almaty plays in the Kazakhstan Hockey Championship.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The city's primary football team is FC Kairat founded in 1954 and one of the most successful Kazakh clubs.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The club made history by qualifying for the 2025-26 UEFA Champions League, thus becoming only the second Kazakhstani football club to do so.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Futsal club AFC Kairat has won the UEFA Futsal Cup in 2012–13 and 2014–15.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Basketball team BC Almaty won the 2015 and 2016 editions of the Kazakhstan Basketball Cup.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Following the successful hosting of the 2011 Winter Asian Games, Almaty made a bid to host the XXII Olympic Winter Games in 2014, but was eliminated from consideration, not making the "short list" of candidate cities.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty was the 2017 Winter Universiade host.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The city was exploring possible bids, such as the 2018 Winter Olympics, but did not submit one.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty submitted a bid to host the 2022 Winter Olympics in August 2013, but lost to Beijing.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] Almaty may still consider to submit a bid to host the 2030 Winter Olympics.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The International Monetary Fund announced in October 2019 that it would launch a new regional technical assistance centre (RTAC) in Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The centre will provide capacity development services to nine IMF member countries in the CCAM region.
[src:aport-apple/alma-ata] The centre is expected to cover the fiscal policy, central bank operations, financial sector supervision, and macroeconomic statistics.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The **Aport** (Russian: Апорт; Kazakh: Апорт алмасы) is a cultivar group of the domesticated apple (*Malus domestica*) most strongly associated with the foothills of the Trans-Ili Alatau around Almaty in southeastern Kazakhstan.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The fruit is unusually large for a dessert apple: typical specimens weigh between 200 and 500 grams (7.1 and 17.6 oz), and exceptional ones exceed 800 grams (28 oz).
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Local growers credit the soil and altitude of the Almaty foothills for its strong honey-like aroma and sweet-tart flavour.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The variety's precise origin is contested.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Different accounts trace it to the Balkans, to the Voronezh Governorate of the Russian Empire, or to the Almaty foothills themselves.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The Aport that became famous in the late 19th and 20th centuries is generally said to have been brought to the town of Verny (modern Almaty) in 1865 and crossed in cultivation with the local wild apple *Malus sieversii*.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] It won prizes at international horticultural exhibitions in Paris in 1900 and Mannheim in 1908 and became closely identified with the city of Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The area under its cultivation contracted sharply in the late 20th century; since 2012 the variety has been the subject of state and academic revival programmes in Kazakhstan.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] In January 2024 President of Kazakhstan Kassym-Jomart Tokayev presented the apple to the Director-General of the Food and Agriculture Organization in Rome as Kazakhstan's nominee under the FAO's "One Country One Priority Product" (OCOP) initiative.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The Russian word *aport* (Апорт) was originally a generic name for several large, late-ripening apple cultivars grown in the Russian Empire, rather than a single clonal variety.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The earliest recorded use of "aport" as the name of an apple appears in monastery records dated to 1175, although it is unclear whether this refers to the cultivar group later established near Almaty.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Horticultural literature has identified the variety as Ukrainian, Russian, Turkish or as a native of the Almaty mountains.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Some Kazakhstani writers argue for a Balkan origin, with the variety reaching Central Asia by way of Ukraine and Russia.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] By the second half of the 19th century the most influential strain was growing in the foothills of the Trans-Ili Alatau, in what was then Semirechye Oblast of the Russian Empire.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The seedlings were considered unremarkable in their place of origin, but produced unusually large and aromatic fruit in the new environment, and the resulting cultivar was named after the village.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] In 1914 the senior horticultural inspector S.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Perkovsky reported to the Russian imperial authorities that the Aport apple and the Forest Beauty pear were the two varieties for which "nature has provided suitable conditions" specifically in the surroundings of Verny.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The hybridisation with *Malus sieversii*, the wild Central Asian apple now recognised as the principal ancestor of the domesticated apple, is generally credited with producing the variety's characteristic size and flavour.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The Slow Food Foundation's Ark of Taste catalogue states that the Aport "developed into the high quality fruit that it is today" only after orchards were established in the Alatau mountains.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Aport apples are large to very large by European dessert-apple standards.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The Slow Food Foundation gives an average fruit weight of 220–250 grams (7.8–8.8 oz), with single fruits reaching 800 grams (28 oz) or more under favourable conditions.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Other sources report typical weights of 200–300 grams (7.1–10.6 oz), occasional fruits approaching 1 kilogram (2.2 lb), and the related Aport Alexander reaching about 900 grams (32 oz).
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The fruit is broadly round to slightly heart-shaped and tapers towards the base.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The skin is thick, smooth and waxy, with a yellow to greenish-yellow ground colour overlaid by bright red striping and blush, sometimes with a brownish-red russet near the stem.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The flesh is pale yellow-green, fine-grained and crisp at harvest, becoming softer and crumblier as the fruit matures in storage.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Tasters describe the aroma as honey-like, with secondary notes of hazelnut and anise.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] In its main area of cultivation harvest takes place in the second half of September, and the fruit keeps under traditional cool storage until mid-January or early February; modern controlled-atmosphere storage extends this until June.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Local growers have traditionally stored the apples under straw to ripen and dried them for winter use; the variety is also processed into juice, compote, jam and baked goods.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] A number of forms are recognised within the Aport group.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Within Kazakhstan, Aport apples are grown principally in the foothills of the Trans-Ili Alatau and the Dzungarian Alatau, at altitudes between roughly 850 and 1,250 metres (2,790 and 4,100 ft).
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The southern districts of Zhambyl Region and Turkistan Region, as well as lower elevations of the Almaty Region, are not recommended; quality fruit reportedly cannot be produced reliably below about 850 metres (2,790 ft).
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The cultivar is considered demanding to grow.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] It is slow to come into bearing, with first crops appearing seven to ten years after planting, compared with three to five years for varieties such as *Golden Delicious* or *Starkrimson*.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] It also tends towards strong biennial fruiting, with abundant crops in one year often followed by a much reduced harvest the next.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Specialists at the Kazakh Research Institute of Fruit Growing and Viticulture have developed drip irrigation systems specifically for Aport orchards, intended to maintain the soil-moisture conditions in which the variety is most productive.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The Aport is widely described in the Kazakhstani and international press as the "calling card" of Almaty, whose Kazakh name is most often translated as "Father of Apples" or "place of abundance of apples"; the city's earlier Russian name Alma-Ata carries the same meaning.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The fruit appears widely in the city's visual culture, including murals, public sculptures, the apple-shaped "Alma" Wishing Fountain in Kok-Tobe Park, and the name of one of the country's largest shopping centres, the Aport Mall on the western edge of the city.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] In 2002 Kazpost issued an "Ile-Alatau National Park" postal block featuring an image of an Aport Alexander apple.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] On 18 February 2009 the National Bank of Kazakhstan released a 500-tenge commemorative coin dedicated to the Almaty Aport.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The annual AlmaFest festival, held in Almaty in September, is centred on the city's apple heritage and on the Aport in particular, with masterclasses, an open-air contemporary art exhibition and a market of regional varieties.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] In international media the Aport is often treated as the cultivated counterpart to the wild *Malus sieversii* from which the modern apple descends.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] *Smithsonian* magazine in 2023 described the campaign to obtain a geographical indication for the Aport, comparable to the protected status of Parmesan cheese or Champagne wine, as part of a wider effort to draw attention to the apple forests of southern Kazakhstan.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] According to the Kazakhstani Ministry of Agriculture, the country had about 3.85 million Aport trees in 1970, of which roughly 79 per cent (about 3.04 million) were concentrated in the Almaty Region.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] By 1984 the total had fallen to about 1.4 million.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] The decline accelerated in the 1990s, when the privatisation of orchard land in the Almaty foothills was followed by widespread clearance of older Aport plantations and the construction of suburban housing in their place.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Saule Kazybayeva, deputy chair of the board of the Kazakh Research Institute of Fruit Growing and Viticulture, has attributed the contraction of the variety to a combination of urbanisation, the Aport's slow entry into bearing, and competition from earlier-bearing varieties such as Golden Delicious.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] She also points to the loss of the traditional practice of grafting Aport scions onto wild *M. sieversii* rootstock, which she argues is necessary to maintain the cultivar's flavour.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] International attention to the variety dates from the early 2000s.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] In 2005 the International Labour Organization launched a project in Kazakhstan to introduce modern cooperative principles among apple farmers in the Taldykorgan region, aiming to help small producers compete with imports through collective action and vocational training.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] Around the same time, efforts to revive the Almaty aport variety specifically were reported by BBC News, which highlighted government and local initiatives to restore orchards in the city's foothills.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] A more sustained scientific revival began in 2012, when the biotechnology laboratory of the KazNII, then under the late professor Magzhan Issin, started selecting individual Aport types and freeing them from accumulated viral infections.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] In 2024 the Ministry of Agriculture and the National Agrarian Scientific and Educational Centre announced a state Aport revival programme running from 2024 to 2028.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] In January 2024 President Tokayev presented Aport apples to FAO Director-General Qu Dongyu in Rome and announced the variety's inclusion in the FAO's "One Country One Priority Product" initiative, launched in 2021 to promote agricultural products of distinctive geographical and cultural character.
[src:aport-apple/aport-apple] As of 2024 total Aport plantings in the Almaty and Zhetysu regions were reported to cover about 2,500 hectares (6,200 acres), comprising roughly 416,000 trees.
